type": "Answer", "text": "Conservative investors should look for sponsors with 5+ completed syndications including full cycle exits (purchased, operated, and sold properties). This demonstrates capability across the entire investment lifecycle, not just acquisition and stabilization. Sponsors with 3-5 deals might be acceptable if you invest smaller amounts or if they have extensive commercial real estate experience from institutional backgrounds before syndicating. First or second-time sponsors carry substantially higher risk regardless of how impressive their presentations or backgrounds appear. If you do invest with newer sponsors, invest smaller amounts ($25,000-$50,000) rather than six-figure commitments until they've proven themselves through actual performance."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How do I verify a sponsor's claimed track record is accurate?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Request detailed spreadsheets listing every deal with property names, addresses, acquisition dates, sale dates (if applicable), purchase prices, sale prices, total investor capital, total distributions, and IRRs. Cross-reference properties against public property records confirming actual purchase and sale prices match sponsor claims. Contact investors from exited deals verifying they received returns matching sponsor representations. Search for the sponsor's name and property names in news articles or press releases confirming major transactions actually occurred. For deals still operating, verify the sponsor actually owns and operates properties by checking property ownership records and speaking with property management. Discrepancies between sponsor claims and public records are serious red flags requiring explanation or disqualification."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "What are the most common due diligence mistakes that cost investors money?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "The five most costly mistakes are: (1) Skipping reference checks and investing based on presentations alone without speaking to past investors. (2) Accepting sponsor-provided financials without independent verification through rent rolls, bank statements, or third-party audits. (3) Not stress-testing underwriting assumptions to see how returns perform with modest changes to rent growth, occupancy, expenses, or exit cap rates. (4) Rushing decisions under artificial urgency without completing thorough legal document review and market research. (5) Investing amounts exceeding your comfortable loss level\u2014never invest capital you cannot afford to lose completely. Each mistake stems from prioritizing speed or trust over verification, a pattern that consistently leads to avoidable losses."}}]};
